04394nam a22006975i 9786155225819DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222014hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9786155225819  a(DE-B1597)633621  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aDR15b.T738 2014 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a914.9604/382231 aNopcsa, Franz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTraveler, Scholar, Political Adventurer :bA Transylvanian Baron at the Birth of Albanian Independence: The memoirs of Franz Nopcsa /cRobert Elsie, Franz Nopcsa. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (250 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Initial Travels (1903–1904) -- tPart II. Research in Albania (1905–1910) -- tPart III. Between the Annexation and the Balkan War (1910–1912) -- tPart IV. From the Balkan War to the World War (1912–1914) -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Personal and Place Names -- tGlossary of Place Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Austro-Hungarian aristocrat of Transylvanian origin, Baron Franz Nopcsa (1877-1933), was one of the most adventuresome travelers and scholars of Southeast Europe in the early decades of the twentieth century. He was also a paleontologist of renown and a noted geologist of the Balkan Peninsula : many of his assumptions have been confirmed by science. The Memoirs of this fascinating figure deal mainly with his travels in the Balkans, and specifically in the remote and wild mountains of northern Albania, in the years from 1903 to 1914. They thus cover the period of Ottoman Rule, the Balkan Wars and the outbreak of the First World War. Nopcsa was a keen adventurer who hiked through regions of northern Albania. With time, he became a leading expert in Albanian studies. He was also deeply involved in the politics of the period. In 1913, Nopcsa even offered himself as a candidate for the vacant Albanian throne. The Introduction also tells of Nopcsa's tragic death: he shot his Albanian secretary and partner before killing himself. The memoirs themselves reveal some references to his homosexuality for those who can read between the lines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAlbania -- Description and travel. 0aBalkan Peninsula -- Description and travel. 0aBalkan Peninsula -- History -- 20th century. 0aNopcsa, Ferencz, -- báró, -- 1877-1933 -- Travel -- Albania. 0aNopcsa, Ferencz, -- báró, -- 1877-1933 -- Travel -- Balkan Peninsula. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aAlbania, Balkan, Biography, Habsburg Empire, History, Memoir, Ottoman Empire, Travel, World War I.1 aElsie, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aElsie, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078054340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155225819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155225819/original  a978-3-11-078054-3  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK